description:
Cheater&rsquo;s Game is a simple competitive game with a straightforward goal: End the tenth round with the highest score. Your score consists of two types of points: honest points and points you have from cheater&rsquo;s alliances. Honest points are completely risk-free, but they&rsquo;re harder to accumulate. Cheater&rsquo;s alliance points are easy to accumulate, and accumulate faster when you have many players in your alliance. However, any member of an alliance can turn the other members of the alliance in and take the alliance's points, adding them to their honest score. So the question is, &ldquo;How far you trust a group of self-admitted cheaters?&rdquo;

Cheater&rsquo;s Game uses about five standard six-sided dice, two point trackers, a turn tracker, player score pawns, and several sets of cheater&rsquo;s alliance pawns.  The trackers and pawns you need to play are all available as a 284 KB PDF.

Cheater&rsquo;s Game has fairly simple rules, but complex psychosocial dynamics. You could play it with children as young as 6 or 7, and use it as a tool for teaching ethical and social lessons. Cheater&rsquo;s Game is appropriate for Ages 12 and up without adult supervision. A 4-player game takes about 45 minutes to play.

This expansion to Nuke Norway Now adds a third player.

Adolf Quisling, Vidkun Quislings until recently known child, Has made himself immortal with genetic experiments and learned the secret of raising the dead.  
This is a new game system for the Zombie-player -- The Zombie-player doesn't use points, he moves every zombie. From the start Adolf Quisling has no zombies and no  power. But when Sweden & Norway attack each other, all killed units are exchanged for Zombies in empty squares. A normal zombie-unit (A small group of zombies) has only 1Attack 1Defence 2Move, but if the human players let the zombies join forces they get stronger and stronger and Adolf Quisling's Raise-dead power increases.

Expands:

    Nuke Norway Now


